Yes — there are two real bootstrap script bugs showing before the workflow summary, and the rest of the green Ansible output that says failed: false is not a failure.

failed: false means the task result object is saying “this task did not fail.” Same with changed: false. Those are good.

The real issues are these:

ERROR: --provision-extra-repo must be OS:ID=PATH_OR_URL
grep: : No such file or directory
WARNING: No provisioning repos were detected for group_vars.

That is happening because the script is building the controller vars even during --bootstrap-only, and because the empty PROVISION_EXTRA_REPOS array is being looped over like it has one blank item.

Fix 1 — only build PXE/controller vars when those playbooks run

Replace this part near the bottom:

BOOTSTRAP_VARS_FILE="$(write_bootstrap_vars_file)"
PXE_VARS_FILE="$(write_pxe_vars_file)"
CONTROLLER_VARS_FILE="$(write_controller_vars_file)"

with this:

BOOTSTRAP_VARS_FILE="$(write_bootstrap_vars_file)"
PXE_VARS_FILE="$(make_temp_file)"
CONTROLLER_VARS_FILE="$(make_temp_file)"
if [[ "${RUN_PXE}" == true ]]; then
  PXE_VARS_FILE="$(write_pxe_vars_file)"
fi
if [[ "${RUN_CONTROLLER}" == true ]]; then
  CONTROLLER_VARS_FILE="$(write_controller_vars_file)"
fi

That prevents --bootstrap-only from touching provisioning repo/group-vars logic at all.

Fix 2 — fix the empty PROVISION_EXTRA_REPOS loop

Replace the first part of this function:

add_extra_provision_repos_to_file() {
  local file="$1"
  local entry=""
  local left=""

with this:

add_extra_provision_repos_to_file() {
  local file="$1"
  local entry=""
  local left=""
  local source=""
  local os_key=""
  local repo_short=""
  local repo_id=""
  local repo_name=""
  local baseurl=""
  if [[ ${#PROVISION_EXTRA_REPOS[@]} -eq 0 ]]; then
    return 0
  fi

Then make sure the loop is this:

for entry in "${PROVISION_EXTRA_REPOS[@]}"; do

not this:

for entry in "${PROVISION_EXTRA_REPOS[@]:-}"; do

That [@]:- pattern is what made Bash treat the empty array like one blank item.

Fix 3 — guard the repo vars file before grep

Inside write_controller_vars_file(), replace this block:

repo_vars_file="$(detect_bundle_provision_repos)"
if grep -q '^  rhel[0-9]' "${repo_vars_file}"; then
  echo "group_vars_defaults_manage_extra_blocks: true" >> "${file}"

with this:

if ! repo_vars_file="$(detect_bundle_provision_repos)"; then
  fail "Failed to build provisioning repo variable file."
fi
if [[ ! -f "${repo_vars_file}" ]]; then
  fail "Provisioning repo variable file was not created correctly."
fi
if grep -q '^  rhel[0-9]' "${repo_vars_file}"; then
  echo "group_vars_defaults_manage_extra_blocks: true" >> "${file}"

That gets rid of the grep: : No such file or directory problem.

Optional but worth adding — force bundle repos for Ansible install

Your test installed ansible-core from existing repos first. That worked, but it pulled from repos like foreman-plugins and local-rh8app, which might not be what you want in a clean offline bundle test.

I would add this default:

PREFER_BUNDLE_REPOS=false

Add this argument:

--prefer-bundle-repos)
  PREFER_BUNDLE_REPOS=true
  shift
  ;;

Then in install_ansible_if_needed(), right after:

info "ansible-playbook is not currently installed."
info "Trying existing configured repositories first."

add:

if [[ "${PREFER_BUNDLE_REPOS}" == true ]]; then
  info "Using bundle BaseOS/AppStream repos first because --prefer-bundle-repos was used."
  resolve_repo_sources "${OS_MAJOR}" || fail "Unable to locate valid BaseOS/AppStream sources automatically. Use --repo-source or --baseos-source/--appstream-source."
  baseos_baseurl="$(to_baseurl "${BASEOS_SOURCE}")"
  appstream_baseurl="$(to_baseurl "${APPSTREAM_SOURCE}")"
  configure_bootstrap_repo_file "${baseos_baseurl}" "${appstream_baseurl}"
  if [[ "${DRY_RUN}" == true ]]; then
    info "DRY RUN: would install ansible-core from bundle bootstrap repos."
    return 0
  fi
  as_root dnf --disablerepo='*' \
    --enablerepo='aerolit-bootstrap-baseos' \
    --enablerepo='aerolit-bootstrap-appstream' \
    install -y ansible-core
  command -v ansible-playbook >/dev/null 2>&1 || fail "ansible-playbook is still not available after ansible-core installation"
  return 0
fi

Then you can test the bundle-controlled path with:

./bootstrap.sh \
  --bootstrap-only \
  --prefer-bundle-repos

About the Ansible role syntax failure

This one is separate from the bootstrap script. The error was from the role task name:

- name: 01. Check destination {{ repo_environment_init_path_item.dest_rel }}

You already fixed it, but make sure any task name with Jinja is quoted:

- name: "01. Check destination {{ repo_environment_init_path_item.dest_rel }}"

Check these files for the same issue:

roles/repo_environment_init/tasks/copy_managed_path.yml
roles/repo_environment_init/tasks/backup_item.yml

Any task name with {{ ... }} should be wrapped in quotes.

